Create a mermaid diagram depicting the nb-wrangler workflow for managing notebook data.
The workflow has these steps.

1. The wrangler spec specifies repos to download.

2. The nb-wrangler --curate-data command clones all of the selected repos.

3. Each repo may include a refdata_dependencies file that specifies:

   1. Named groups of data to download
   2. Within each group N web references of archive files to download
   3. The paths at which the archives should be unpacked
   4. A "nested root" within each archive under which data really exists
   5. An evironment variable that points to the group's data location: 3+4

4. nb-wrangler adds the refdata_dependencies.yaml file to the spec.  There can
   be only refdata file so if more than two repositories are specified the
   "winner" is selected using the system.primary_repo field.

5. nb-wrangler downloads and unpacks the archive files, nominally under its
   "pantry" directory.

6. For each archive file,  nb-wrangler computes a sha256 and adds it to the
   spec for verification of future installations.

7. nb-wrangler generates environment variable files in two formats: refdata
   format fully adheres to the installation locations defined by
   refdata_dependencies.yaml.  the second format defines paths relative to
   the "pantry" directory where shared and/or archived files are stored.
   In both cases, the env var files define valid paths on the file system.

8. The wrangler injects environment variable definitions into the kernel .json
   file automatically definining them for the notebook environment.  A wrangler
   command can output export definitions suitable for initializing a shell
   environment for use with terminals.
